		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Terry Eagleton</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Terry_Eagleton_in_Manchester_2008.jpg" class="image" title="Terry Eagleton holding one of his books after a talk in Manchester Mechanics' Institute in 2008"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/7/76/Terry_Eagleton_in_Manchester_2008.jpg/180px-Terry_Eagleton_in_Manchester_2008.jpg" width="180" height="240" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Terry_Eagleton_in_Manchester_2008.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Terry Eagleton holding one of his books after a talk in Manchester Mechanics' Institute in 2008</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Terence Francis Eagleton</b> (born 22 February 1943, <a href="/wiki/Salford" title="Salford">Salford</a> then in <a href="/wiki/Lancashire" title="Lancashire">Lancashire</a>) is a <a href="/wiki/British_people" title="British people">British</a> <a href="/wiki/Literary_theorist" title="Literary theorist" class="mw-redirect">literary theorist</a> and critic, regarded by some as Britain's most influential living <a href="/wiki/Literary_critic" title="Literary critic" class="mw-redirect">literary critic</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Formerly Eagleton was <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Wharton" title="Thomas Wharton">Thomas Wharton</a> Professor of English Literature at the University of Oxford (1992-2001) and <a href="/wiki/John_Edward_Taylor" title="John Edward Taylor">John Edward Taylor</a> Professor of English Literature at the University of Manchester until 2008. In October 2008, Terry Eagleton was appointed to a Chair in English Literature at the Department of English &amp; Creative Writing at <a href="/wiki/Lancaster_University" title="Lancaster University">Lancaster University</a>. He also holds a visiting professorship at <a href="/wiki/National_University_of_Ireland,_Galway" title="National University of Ireland, Galway">National University of Ireland, Galway</a>.</p>
<p>He has written more than forty books, including <i>Literary Theory: An Introduction</i> (1983);<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> <i>The Ideology of the Aesthetic</i> (1990), and <i>The Illusions of Postmodernism</i> (1996).</p>
<p>He will give a <a href="/wiki/Gifford_Lectures" title="Gifford Lectures">Gifford Lecture</a> in March 2010, titled <i>The God Debate</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
